               <p>WILLIAM HAZLE PAIN TWYFORD. I was in <placeName id="t18260406-111-crimeloc585">Piccadilly</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260406-111-crimeloc585" type="placeName" value="Piccadilly"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260406-111-crimeloc585" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260406-111-off583 t18260406-111-crimeloc585"></join> about twenty minutes after three o'clock, on the 8th of March; a gentleman tapped me on the shoulder, and said the prisoner had taken my handkerchief from me; he had him at that time by the collar; I took hold of him likewise, and he immediately gave me my handkerchief from his pocket - I took him to the watch-house.</p>
               <p>Prisoner I picked it up, and put it into my pocket, the gentleman came, and took me. Witness. He did not say he picked it up.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260406-111-person658">
                  THOMAS 
                  LOVEGROVE
               <interp inst="t18260406-111-person658" type="surname" value="LOVEGROVE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260406-111-person658" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260406-111-person658" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am the watch-house-keeper. The prisoner was brought to me there; he was begging<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182604060053"></xptr>of Mr. Twyford not to prosecute him. There was another gentleman who said, in his presence, he saw him take it from the prosecutor's pocket - but he was obliged to leave town on business - a duplicate of another handkerchief was found on him.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260406-111-verdict586" type="verdictDescription">
